data.name: The awesome Intel recruiting ad typo I wrote about the other day.

data.message: does the asterisk say "get it?"
I think what they are saying is that Windows has now been renamed to just Window and it is sentient.  You will actually work for Window as it's architect.
So why is it capitalized as a proper noun, yet has the indefinite article? Otherwise sort of works: "Join our privacy team as a window's curtains, shade or blinds."
Laura, the asterisk says "Other names and brands may be claimed as the property of others"... Which is amazingly vague.
...meaning that they aren't calling it Windows(TM), which isn't supposed to be used in the possessive: http://www.microsoft.com/about/legal/en/us/intellectualproperty/trademarks/usage/windows.aspx
But that still doesn't explain why the title uses sentence capitalization rules, while the sentence uses title capitalization rules.
omg.  i just read what i wrote.  i got the ' wrong on its.
Beau: with that definition they probably need to put an asterisk next to every word in the ad.
Marc,how do you know they aren't hiring a team to work on a window...like a display for a Linux tablet...and the window is so important they capitalize it?
I use apostrophe's on all the plural noun's that I use just to be on the safe side.

data.name: This is a criminally stupid waste of money and plastic.

data.message: Since the umbrella-drying problem has long been known to be intractable, I for one am glad I can lock the moisture into a convenient plastic bag.
At least that sort of thing doesn't really exist many other places around the area, since only out-of-towners ever carry umbrellas. :)
I wonder if these could be a choking hazard? ..Cuz that shit looks tasty.
I actually asked what the deal was. Apparently they think if people bring wet umbrellas through the lobby someone might slip and die (or sue).
Doesn't every one know you are supposed to spin them like you are in a musical before going indoors?
so THATS why you spin them!  everything important i know about life i learned from Keith Kemp
Wait wait!!!  this is at the Washington convention center! isn't that in the city that charges a TAX for using plastic bags at the super market

The bag tax was repealed in 2009 after being active for a year; Seattle apparently just banned plastic bags two weeks ago though: http://www.seattlepi.com/local/article/Plastic-bags-banned-in-Seattle-2412950.php
